'''Matti Kullervo Seppälä''' (born 5 September 1941 in [[Vaasa]]) is a [[Finnish people|Finnish]] [[geomorphology|geomorphologist]] specialized in cold climate [[aeolian processes]].<ref>{{cite book | editor=Ellonen, Leena | title=Suomen professorit. Finlands professorer: 1640–2007 | page=664 | location=Helsinki | publisher=Professoriliitto | year=2008 | isbn=978-952-99281-1-8 }}</ref> Seppälä is arguably the foremost expert on [[palsa]]s.<ref name=Durham>{{cite web |url=https://www.dur.ac.uk/ias/fellows/cofundfellows/srf1314/seppala/ |title=Professor Matti Seppälä |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= |website=Durham University |publisher= |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> Seppälä obtained a [[Ph.D.]] at the [[University of Turku]] in 1971 and moved after to work at the [[University of Oulu]] until in 1978 he moved to the [[University of Helsinki]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Seppälä |first=Matti |date=2004 |title=Wind as Geomorphic Agent in Cold Climates (Frontmatter) |url=http://assets.cambridge.org/97805215/64069/frontmatter/9780521564069_frontmatter.pdf |location= |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |page= |isbn=0 521 56406 9 |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref> He served at that university as professor from 1978 to 2009<ref name=Helsinki/> and is currently a retired professor of [[physical geography]] at that university.<ref name=Durham/><ref name=Helsinki>{{cite web |url=http://www.helsinki.fi/geography/Matti_Seppala_eng.html |title=Matti Seppälä |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=October 29, 2013 |website=University of Helsinki |publisher= |accessdate=August 21, 2014}}</ref>
Matti Seppälä has also been a [[research fellow]] at [[Uppsala University]], [[Heidelberg University]], [[Université de Montréal]], [[University of Cambridge]] and [[Durham University]].<ref name=Helsinki/>
==Notable publications== *''Wind as Geomorphic Agent in Cold Climates''. [[Cambridge University Press]] (2004). {{ISBN|0 521 56406 9}} *The origin of palsas. ''[[Geografiska Annaler]]'' 68A (1986), p.&nbsp;141-147.
